I"é"<p>PHP and HTML are totally different languages. PHP is a server-side language while the HTML is a client-side language. However the interaction between these two is very important. We make the interface in html while and we write the logic in php. The simple example of it is the sign-up boxes. They are made in html, while the username and password we enter in the fields is taken to server via the use of php. So both of them are of equal importance.</p>

<p>Client sends request to the server. There are 2 types of requests.</p>

<ul>
  <li>get request</li>
  <li>post request</li>
</ul>

<p>In get request, the address is visible in the address bar, while post request is much more secure and the address is not shown in the address bar.</p>

<p>You can also check the working of php by checking out this blog <a href="/2020/10/08/how-php-works">How PHP Works??</a></p>

<h2 id="get-request-method">GET Request Method</h2>

<p>One way of getting data in php is <strong>GET</strong> request method. Simply youâ€™ve to do 4 steps for this purpose,</p>

<ul>
  <li>Make HTML file</li>
  <li>Make PHP file</li>
  <li>Make input field in HTML file</li>
  <li>Recieve data in PHP file</li>
</ul>

<p>First of all letâ€™s make an html file, name it <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">login.html</code>. Create a basic form in this file with two input fields and 1 button. Also keep in mind, youâ€™ve to write <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">form method="get"</code> for the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">get</code> request and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">action="./login.php"</code> for the redirection. At the end of form make a button as well. Here is the code,</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
    &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Login&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;form method="get" action="./login.php"&gt;
        &lt;input type="text" name="user_name" placeholder="Enter User Name"/&gt;
        &lt;br /&gt;
        &lt;br /&gt;
        &lt;input type="text" name="user_password" placeholder="Enter User Password"/&gt;
        &lt;br/&gt;
        &lt;br/&gt;
        &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Login&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
    
    
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/1.png" alt="1" /></p>

<p>Now make the php file with the name <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">login.php</code>. Write a simple <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">echo</code> with a text in it,</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php
echo "this is a php login file";
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Now write a username and password on the webpage,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/2.png" alt="2" /></p>

<p>Press the <strong>submit</strong> button and youâ€™ll get,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/3.png" alt="3" /></p>

<p><strong>GET</strong> request has three characteristics,</p>

<ul>
  <li>Request is visible in the address bar</li>
  <li>Less secure request</li>
  <li>Mostly used to get data from the server</li>
</ul>

<p>As you know you get the information of the <strong>GET</strong> request in the address bar, here is how it looks.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/4.png" alt="4" /></p>

<p>You can also print these values using php. Here it is how you do it,</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php
echo "user name is ".$_GET['user_name'];
echo "&lt;br/&gt;";
echo "user password is ".$_GET['user_password'];
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/5.png" alt="5" /></p>

<p>The url portion after <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">?</code> represents the values of <strong>GET</strong> request. What if remove the portion after <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">?</code> in the url. What will we get? Lets check this,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/6.png" alt="6" /></p>

<p>You will get the warning about the undefined array key of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">user name</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">user password</code>,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/7.png" alt="7" /></p>

<p>Now how to remove this warning, you simply have to write a single <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">if</code> check in order to avoid this warning.</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php

if($_GET){
    // echo "this is a php login file";
    echo "user name is ".$_GET['user_name'];
    echo "&lt;br/&gt;";
    echo "user password is ".$_GET['user_password'];
}
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Now if there is nothing after <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">?</code>, youâ€™ll not get any warning. Instead youâ€™ll get a simple white blank page.
The <strong>GET</strong> request information is also available if you <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">inspect</code> the page on your browser and go to the payload of the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Network</code>,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/8.png" alt="8" /></p>

<p>P.S, you can check the type of the request by clicking the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Headers</code> tab.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/9.png" alt="9" /></p>

<h2 id="post-request-method">POST Request Method</h2>

<p>Another way of getting data in php is <strong>POST</strong> request method. You also have to do same 4 steps for this type of request,</p>

<ul>
  <li>Make HTML file</li>
  <li>Make PHP file</li>
  <li>Make input field in HTML file</li>
  <li>Recieve data in PHP file</li>
</ul>

<p>We are creating two files now,</p>
<ul>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">signup.html</code></li>
  <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">signup.php</code></li>
</ul>

<p>Simply create an html file with a basic form code in it. Keep in mind youâ€™ve to write <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">method="post"</code> in the form tag. Here is a complete code for the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">signup.html</code> file</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
    &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Sign Up&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;form method="post" action="./signup.php"&gt;
        &lt;input type="text" placeholder="enter name" name="user_name"/&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;input type="text" placeholder="enter password" name="user_password"&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;input type="text" placeholder="enter email" name="user_email"&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;br&gt;
        &lt;button&gt;Sign Up&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
    
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Now create the other file <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">signup.php</code>. In this file simply use the if condition with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$_POST</code> request and simply use the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">print_r()</code> function to print out all the values from the post request.</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php 
//echo "signup page";
if($_POST){
    print_r($_POST);
}
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Now go to the <strong>Sign Up</strong> page and fill out the information,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/10.png" alt="10" /></p>

<p>click the <strong>Sign Up</strong> button and here is the information,</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/clt/html-with-php/11.png" alt="11" /></p>

<p>You can also print out the information separately,</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php 
echo "signup page";
if($_POST){
    print_r($_POST);
    echo "&lt;br&gt;";
    echo "User Name is: ".$_POST['user_name']."&lt;br&gt;";
    echo "User Password is: ".$_POST['user_password']."&lt;br&gt;";
    echo "User Email is: ".$_POST['user_email']."&lt;br&gt;";
}
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>
